<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Recessions">Recessions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Funding_of_science&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Recessions"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In crisis, business R&amp;D tends to act <a href="/wiki/Procyclical_and_countercyclical_variables" title="Procyclical and countercyclical variables">procyclically</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup> As R&amp;D is a long-term investments and so disruptions should be avoided Keynesian <a href="/wiki/Procyclical_and_countercyclical_variables" title="Procyclical and countercyclical variables">countercyclical</a> reactions were advocated for in the wake of the 2008 financial crisis, but this was difficult to achieve for some countries.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup> Due to the nature of COVID-19, the pandemic accelerated publicly funded R&amp;D spending in 2020, primarily into the <a href="/wiki/Pharmaceutical_industry" title="Pharmaceutical industry">pharmaceutical industry</a>. A fall is expected in spending for 2021, although not below 2020 levels.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> The pandemic made health research and sectors with strategic value-chain dependencies the main target of science funding.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
